>>1181fddc-ebc0-48d9-8a8a-30d45e34425c
The problem is that the barrier to entry is why this place isn't utter dogshit. Remember the internet before the Eternal September? It took a bit of knowledge and a bit of effort to get there, and as such, the people who showed up were usually willing to actually try once they were there. 4chan, being a website with a reputation in the early days of the internet, was in a similar position, but with the election of Trump and the proliferation of the Q meme, it's safe to say that they've had their Eternal September. I think that, the current process for coming here, (download program, find site, turn on torposting, get zeroid) is perfect: simple and easy, the only people who can fuck it up are people who know less than nothing and people who don't give a shit, which are the exact kinds of people we don't want.
People don't just wander in and make awful posts because they have no clue what they're doing, and they also don't just pop over and drop a few shill/slide/spam posts because they can. Most trolls aren't actually that dedicated. Wall out the bottom 10% of effort and you wall out 50% of trolls.

Add in Nixon, and less than half of the Presidents who were voted in and didn't see 8 years did so because they failed reelection. Incumbent advantage is huge. As for my predictions, Trump wins 2020, since it was a minor miracle that he won 2016 and the field is now even more in his favor as before. Republicans learn to stay out of his way faster than last time. The democrats will likely run someone like Hillary, but with less baggage and equally less draw. On the chance that they do take a big risk, it will be some Occasio-Cortez type who practically turns the field into "people who like her" vs "people who's opinions actually get listened to".
The alternative leftist movements broadly continue to play the wife in pic related, with the liberals as the husband. Wouldn't be the first time communists forgot that "ally-of-convenience" goes both ways. The alternative right movements get their shit together a little. Maybe some of them even start on the path to being important. We'll find out which ones did it, if any, in '24-'28.
China has probably hit the wall already. Systems like theirs tend to be good at keeping a lid on problems like they have, but they come out eventually. It will probably survive the next four years, and it might even seem stronger at the end, but the size of the problems that they need to sweep under the rug swiftly outpaces the size of the rug they have. Mao's disastrous reign, and his successor's poorly thought out ideas, might even put warlords back in power within the next few decades. Who wants to get back into dynastic politics should get reading, since Taiwan is still there.

The rest of Europe will continue to stew in it's bitterness about being placed behind foreigners. Extend the timeframe a bit longer, and you will likely have some real issues, but I don't want to make concrete predictions beyond 2024. I've heard rumors of a massive reccession brewing. I can't say I know about that, but if it happens, add a few more points of European chaos into the models.
America will still be a democracy at the end of it all (say, at ~2030). Some of Europe might not, but America will. America has always been resistant to non-voting systems of government, and that still has a bit of life in it.
Technology is getting into territory where it's being made faster than it can be used. That said, barring any massive technological developments, '20-'24 will be like now except a bit *more*.
